  "text": "exists in two homologous isoforms, there is only one mature isoform of miR-7 in humans, encoded by three different loci. Importantly, human miR-7 shares sequence identity with mouse miR-7a [CITATION_1] . To investigate the role of miR-7 in human b-cell proliferation, we transfected dispersed human islet cells with control oligonucleotide or antimiR-7a inhibitor. Only 0.01% of Ki67-positive b-cells were detected in the control group, in agreement with previous observations [CITATION_2] . In striking contrast, the number of Ki67-positive insulin-expressing human b-cells increased nearly 30-fold in the setting of miR-7a deficiency (Fig. 6A, B) . As in mouse islets, miR-7 deficiency caused an activation of mTOR signaling in human islets. Both total and phosphorylated eIF4E protein levels were upregulated by suppression of miR-7, as was the level of phosphorylated S6 (Supplementary Fig. 2 ). These findings indicate that miR-7a negatively regulates the mTOR pathway and b-cell replication in human islets. mTOR signaling is the key pathway mediating miR-7 modulation of primary b-cell proliferation. Recently, several other targets of miR-7 have been reported. The critical developmental transcription factor Pax6 is a newly identified target of miR7 during pancreas development [CITATION_3] . We found that Pax6 also is regulated by miR7 in Min6 cells ( Supplementary Fig. 3A , B) and in adult islets (Supplementary Fig. 3D, E) . Consistent with the regulatory pattern of identified targets in the mTOR pathway, miR-7a deficiency did not affect the mRNA levels of Pax6 (Supplementary Fig. 3C ). Epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR) also has been recognized as a target of miR-7 in the modulation of cell growth in human cancer cells [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] ; however, our bioinformatics analysis did not reveal conservation of the target seed sequence in the 39-UTR of murine EGFR. Accordingly, Western blot analysis demonstrated that EGFR protein levels were not affected by inhibition of miR-7a in Min6 cells ( Supplementary Fig. 4) , suggesting that the increased Min6 cell growth observed after miR-7 inhibition was not mediated by an increase in EGFR expression.",
